 16. Blockers, Challenges, and Lessons Learned
16.1 Preemptive Transaction Lookup — Persistent Blocker
One of the most persistent blockers throughout the EPP program was the incomplete state of Preemptive Transaction Lookup. This architectural improvement was identified as Sequencing Step 1 in the engineering plan but was marked BLOCKED as late as October 2023. The team documented two known gaps that needed resolution before cutover: the missing auto-acceptance logic and the broken notification flow for escalated disputes. The workaround was to potentially proceed without it, accepting the operational complexity of the pending Dispute state during the integration period.
16.2 Snowflake Architecture Pivot
The original design called for Arbiter to connect directly to Fiserv's Snowflake instance using application credentials (to be created by EM David Miller). This was ultimately cancelled. Instead, the architecture shifted to a Snowflake task that runs on Fiserv's side and copies data to S3 for Arbiter to consume. This pivot likely simplified operational security (no direct Snowflake credentials in Arbiter's production config) but required additional work to define and deploy the Snowflake task infrastructure in the snowflake-terraform repo.
16.3 Weekend Adjustment Data Edge Case
After the integration went live, an operational issue was discovered involving dispute records received on weekends. Specifically, when Fiserv processed status updates after their adjustment cutoff on Fridays, those records would arrive in Snowflake with an updated upd_dt but stale or null adjustment data (adj_dt and adj_amt). This caused PREs in Arbiter because the system expected adjustment data to be present for Open chargebacks and Reversal records.
The root cause was a Fiserv system behavior, not a bug in BT code. Fiserv's adjustment processing cannot backfill until the following Monday. Three problematic patterns were identified:
25.	Chargeback/Open records with adj_dt = null and adj_amt = null (when there should be values)
26.	Reversal/Reversed records with adj_dt < upd_dt and adj_amt < 0 (stale, pre-reversal data)
27.	Unknown other combinations that might emerge
16.4 Dual-Pipeline Complexity
Operating two simultaneous dispute pipelines (Wells and Fiserv) during the transition period created significant complexity. For merchants being migrated, Wells disputes from before the cutover date continued to arrive while Fiserv disputes for the same merchant also started flowing. The strategy engine needed to correctly differentiate between these, and the cutover strategies needed to handle 'mid-life' disputes — cases that opened on Wells but received status updates on Fiserv. Sequence diagrams were called out as a needed deliverable to map all these scenarios.
16.5 Partial Credits / Partial Chargebacks
A nuanced financial edge case was discovered via Slack: a credit (representing a partial refund) was received from Wells/Fiserv, but the case should NOT have been closed based on that credit alone. The question was whether Snowflake/Arbiter could reliably detect that a partial credit did not indicate a terminal status. The cb_partialAmountFlag field in the Fiserv data was identified as potentially useful here, but its presence in the original dispute record (vs. only on updates) was an open question.
16.6 Reporting Dependency Gap
Throughout the EPP program, a persistent gap existed between what the Disputes team could deliver technically and what Reporting could deliver on its own timeline. DFR (the long-term DFR for merchant reconciliation) and DDR (the long-term dispute detail report) had no firm ETAs for Control Panel extension. This meant that legacy reports (DFIR, DLR) would need to be maintained longer than originally hoped, delaying the clean deprecation planned for Phase 4+.
 17. PRE Playbook — Operational Incident Handling
A ProcessorRecordException (PRE) is raised when Arbiter receives a dispute record from Fiserv that it cannot handle — either because data is missing/invalid, or because no matching strategy exists for the record's state. The Fiserv PRE Playbook was written by Carla Garcia Dimanche to document common PRE scenarios and the remediation steps for on-call engineers.
17.1 Missing Adjustment Data PRE
17.1.1 Background
The most common PRE type after go-live was caused by missing adjustment data on weekend records. On date D, the Snowflake task queries for records with upd_dt = D-1. Normally, when upd_dt is updated, all related values (adj_dt, adj_amt) are also updated. However, for status updates made after Fiserv's Friday adjustment cutoff, the status update goes through but adjustment data cannot be filled in until the following Monday.
17.1.2 Identification Query
To identify PREs caused by missing adjustment data, run the following against Arbiter's database:
SELECT pre.id, fc.status_date, fc.ids_case_number, fc.arn
FROM fiserv_chargebacks fc
JOIN processor_record_exceptions pre
  ON pre.processor_record_id = fc.id
  AND pre.processor_record_type = 'Fiserv::Chargeback'
WHERE (
  (fc.dispute_type = 'Chargeback' AND fc.chargeback_status = 'Open'
   AND fc.adjustment_date IS NULL AND fc.adjustment_amount IS NULL)
  OR
  (fc.dispute_type = 'Reversal' AND fc.chargeback_status = 'Reversed'
   AND fc.adjustment_date < fc.status_date AND fc.adjustment_amount < 0)
)
AND pre.resolved_at IS NULL AND pre.deleted_at IS NULL
ORDER BY fc.status_date;
17.1.3 Remediation Steps (9-Step Process)
28.	Run the identification query above. Save the PRE IDs, status dates, IDS case numbers, and ARNs.
29.	Manually run the chargebacks query from snowflake-terraform repo against Fiserv's Snowflake instance with WHERE upd_dt = <status_date> AND acqr_ref_no IN (<list of ARNs>).
30.	Download results as CSV named <status_date>_backfilled_records.csv, then gzip it.
31.	Upload gzipped file to S3: bt-production-arbiter-processor-files/fiserv/chargeback/<status_date>/
32.	Enter a Rails console from a support pod in a production cpair.
33.	Execute: Fiserv::FileProcessor.process("fiserv/chargeback/<status_date>/<status_date>_backfilled_records.csv.gz")
34.	Verify processing was successful: query Dispute.allow_unscoped_find.where(case_number: [...]) and check statuses match expected open/won counts.
35.	Verify all open disputes are still within the reply-by window. If any reply-by dates have passed, provide list to Product for merchant reimbursement review.
36.	Mark PREs as resolved: ProcessorRecordException.allow_unscoped_find.where(id: [...]).map(&:resolve)
17.2 PRE Prevention and Long-Term Fix
The playbook noted that a proper automated solution was being designed (referenced as a Slack discussion from 9/20/2023 in #epp-disputes-bk). Until that fix was implemented, the above manual process needed to be run every Monday for weekend records that PREd due to missing adjustment data.
