Summary
Elevate Payment Partnerships (EPP; also known as Control Our Destiny or COD) is an initiative by PayPal to reduce its dependency on third-party banks and processors. As far as Braintree is concerned, this involves shifting our 1,000 largest merchants off of the Wells pipeline and onto a new pipeline consisting of Fiserv as the processor and Goldman Sachs as the acquiring bank. All other merchants would be migrated to the PayPal Commerce Platform (PPCP).
With this new pipeline, BT Disputes will be receiving information about disputes directly from Fiserv. We will also be submitting dispute representments directly to Fiserv. This requires us to build a new end-to-end processor integration with Fiserv.
Fiserv disputes integration
As with our other processor integrations, design can be broken down into three distinct components: ingesting processor records, handling processor records, and representing disputes.
However, this design also assumes that we make a few improvements to Arbiter. Namely, it would be ideal to split up the ingest and handling of processor records into separate jobs, and to cut over to preemptive Gateway transaction lookup. While these changes are not required for a functional integration with any processor, they can improve performance and clarity.
Lastly, a requirement for delivering EPP Phase 4 is to implement a handshake with Funding that can be used to inform Reporting that ingest and handling is complete for the day.
 
 
Ingest
While the source of processor records is not confirmed, the current plan is to connect to and query Fiserv's Snowflake instance. The alternative is receiving a CLX file, likely via SFTP.
Below, "ProcessorRecord" is used as a placeholder for the actual name of Fiserv records (e.g., "ChargebackActivity" for Moneris or "DisputeRecord" for PwV).
A Fiserv::ProcessorRecordIngestRunner should be kicked off by a cron job daily at a given time. This runner will orchestrate retrieving and persisting the day's processor records.
The runner will call a Fiserv::Client that is responsible for connecting to and querying records from Snowflake. The SLA for records to be available in Snowflake is TBD time, TBD days per week.
The runner will iterate through the records – for each one, building a Fiserv::ProcessorRecord object and persisting it to a fiserv_processor_record table in the Arbiter database. The Fiserv::ProcessorRecord model should have validations in accordance with the data that we expect to see on each record. We should raise a ProcessorRecordException (PRE) for each record that has missing or unexpected data.
In the (seemingly likely) event that retrieval records and chargeback records are separate entities living in separate Snowflake tables, we will need a separate model and DB table for both.
Depending on whether Gateway transaction lookup is required for the processor record, the runner will either call the TransactionLookupEventService to create a TransactionLookupEvent and produce the transaction lookup request to the Gateway, or queue a HandleProcessorRecordJob to handle the record. See "Splitting processor record ingest and handling" for more details.
There should also be Datadog metrics that provide insight into whether records are available at the expected time, how long ingest takes, etc.
