Preemptive transaction lookup
Currently, Arbiter handles an open processor record by creating a Dispute in a pending state. Pending Disputes are internal-only and not visible to merchants. Arbiter then kicks off Gateway transaction lookup to get the transaction information for the Dispute. Once the Gateway returns this information, the pending Dispute is transitioned to an open state and made visible to merchants.
With preemptive transaction lookup, Arbiter instead kicks off Gateway transaction lookup before handling the open processor record. When the Gateway returns the transaction information, Arbiter creates a Dispute in an open state. This reduces confusion by doing away with the pending status. When a Dispute is created, it has all the information needed to be visible to merchants.
This Slack thread contains a lot of helpful context: Preemptive transaction lookup Slack thread. Furthermore, this PR contains additional context and was the most recent effort to address gaps in the flow: Fix gaps in pre-emptive transaction lookup #2896.
There are still a few issues with the existing preemptive transaction lookup implementation that need to be resolved before a successful cutover can occur.
1.	Auto acceptance evaluation logic is currently not in place for the preemptive transaction lookup flow. This needs to be added, likely in the DisputeBuilder – it can occur here because preemptive transaction lookup Disputes are created in an open state, and therefore can immediately transition to auto accepted.
2.	Open processor records for escalated cases (i.e., an open chargeback-with-retrieval record or an open pre-arbitration record) will not undergo Gateway transaction lookup, because transaction information will already have been retrieved for the case during the earlier lifecycle stage. This means that open notifications will not be created for the resulting Disputes, because notification creation is currently skipped in the DisputeBuilder for preemptive transaction lookup Disputes. The reason that notification creation is currently skipped is because notifications cannot be created until the Dispute is updated with certain attributes that are provided in the transaction lookup response. We need to refactor our code such that, by the time a processor record is passed to the DisputeBuilder, a Dispute and its notifications can be created with all the necessary information. One solution is to persist dispute attributes returned from the Gateway on the TransactionLookupEvent, so that they can be accessed in the DisputeBuilder.
 
