Representment
When merchants submit evidence for a Dispute, we need to ensure that evidence is submitted to Fiserv in a timely fashion. This will involve creating a new Fiserv::EvidenceSubmissionService. We should also notify Fiserv when a merchant has decided to accept a Dispute, which will involve creating a new Fiserv::DisputeAcceptanceService.
These three documents in the Disputes Knowledge repo are particularly useful for a basic understanding of representment:
•	Evidence Submission Flow
•	Acceptance Flow
•	Representment: Overall Architecture – this is for Wells, and slightly outdated
Based on correspondence with Fiserv, it seems likely that we will submit representments via SFTP. Presumably, we would also receive acknowledgement files via SFTP. If so, we can leverage the existing FirstData::EvidenceSubmissionService, FirstData::DisputeAcceptanceService, BatchSubmissionRunner, and AcknowledgementRunner.
For Braintree, we will leverage the existing mailbox that the current Braintree file is submitted through, and we will be standing up a new file to be sent through that mailbox using the existing transmission job name for BrainTree, which is RCDMBPSS. That eResponse job is built out within the mailbox NAGW-XBMDK006. We will just assign a new eResponse Group ID, and the file name will then be RCDMBPSS.XXXXXXX.D*.T*.zip. The X’s will be replaced once we have the eResponse Group ID value we will be using.
If merchants do not act on a Dispute by the merchant reply-by date, the Dispute will be picked up by the DisputesReadyToExpireQuery and transitioned to an expired state by the ExpiredRunner. If a Dispute has not reached a terminal state after a specified amount of time, it should be picked up by the DisputesReadyToLoseQuery and transitioned to a lost state by the LostRunner.
We currently have logic in the ExpiredRunner to auto-submit Wells disputes that have an amount_disputed over 30 USD and are associated with a transaction that was refunded via Braintree. If we want to maintain parity here, we should ensure that Fiserv disputes are covered by this logic.
